 6 >= 0, i = 2 is a valid split.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n2 <= nums.length <= 105\n-105 <= nums[i] <= 105\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def waysToSplitArray(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def waysToSplitArray(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        total_sum = sum(nums)\n        left_sum = 0\n        valid_splits = 0\n        \n        for i in range(len(nums) - 1):\n            left_sum += nums[i]\n            right_sum = total_sum - left_sum\n            if left_sum >= right_sum:\n                valid_splits += 1\n        \n        return valid_splits\n```\n\nThis solution iterates through the list, maintaining a running sum of the left part of the array (`left_sum`) and calculating the right part of the array (`right_sum`) by subtracting `left_sum` from the total sum of the array. It checks if the `left_sum` is greater than or equal to `right_sum` and counts the number of valid splits accordingly. The loop runs until the second last element to ensure there is at least one element to the right of the split index.", "estimated_date": 1651968000000}